To add an image at the center in Flutter, you can use the `Center` widget along with the `Image` widget. Here's an example:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: Text('Centered Image'),
        ),
        body: Center(
          child: Image.asset('assets/images/my_image.jpg'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

Make sure to replace 'assets/images/my_image.jpg' with the actual path of your image.

Note: Don't forget to add the image file to your project and specify it in `pubspec.yaml` under the `assets` section.
```yaml
flutter:
  assets:
    - assets/images/
```

This example creates a simple Flutter app with a centered image in the body section, wrapped inside the `Center` widget.

If you are using Flutter with the Cloud Firestore database and want to perform a 'like' query, you can use the `where` and `orderBy` methods available in the `Firestore.instance` API. Here's an example:

```dart
import 'package:cloud_firestore/cloud_firestore.dart';

void searchDocumentsByQuery(String substring) {
  Firestore.instance
    .collection('your_collection_name')
    .where('field_name', isGreaterThanOrEqualTo: substring)
    .where('field_name', isLessThanOrEqualTo: substring + '\uf8ff')
    .orderBy('field_name')
    .snapshots()
    .listen((QuerySnapshot snapshot) {
      snapshot.documents.forEach((DocumentSnapshot doc) {
        print('${doc.documentID}: ${doc.data}');
      });
    });
}

// Usage example
searchDocumentsByQuery("search_string");
```

Replace `'your_collection_name'` with the name of your collection and `'field_name'` with the name of the field you want to perform the "like" query on.

The `where` method is used to specify the condition on the field. By using `isGreaterThanOrEqualTo: substring` and `isLessThanOrEqualTo: substring + '\uf8ff'`, you are performing a range query similar to the "like" query. Additionally, the `orderBy` method is used to sort the results based on the field_name.

The `snapshots()` method returns a stream of QuerySnapshot, and `.listen` allows you to listen to changes in the query results. In this example, we iterate over the documents in the snapshot and print their IDs and data.

Remember to add the `cloud_firestore` package to your `pubspec.yaml` file and import it into your Dart file.

Note that Firebase Firestore does not support full-text search functionality out of the box. To achieve more complex search capabilities, you might need to consider implementing a separate search index, or use additional libraries or services designed for search functionality, such as Algolia or ElasticSearch.

